<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-105-294 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 020 020</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  July 16 1991 v5 n25 p30(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIDI programming language adds OMS compatibility, ready-to-usefiles. (Opcode Systems Inc. MAX object-oriented programminglanguage) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown L., Dartanyan.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Opcode Systems Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   Max 2.1 (Program development software) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Object-Oriented ProgrammingMIDIProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Dartanyan L. BrownandM;Menlo Park, Calif -- Opcode Systems Inc. last month released an upgrade toMAX, its object- oriented programming language for Musical Instrument DigitalInterface applications.andM;Originally developed in Paris at IRCAM (Institut de Recherche et deCoordination Acoustique/ Musique), the French computer-music researchfacility (see MacWEEK, Sept.andP;  25, 1990), the $395 application offers aninterface for creating and linking &quot;patches&quot; (MIDI code, video, animation andother multimedia data modules that perform particular functions).andM;Version 2.1 is free to registered users and features the following:andM;andgt;OMS compatibility.andP;  OMS (Opcode MIDI system) allows MAX patches to accessmultiple devices and MIDI channels.andP;  It supports timecode generators, such asMark Of The Unicorn Inc.'s MIDI Timepiece, as well as Opcode's Studio 5.andM;andgt;Ready-to-use applications.andP;  These include controller interfaces for theYamaha DMP-11, Lexicon LXP-5 and Roland Sound Canvas.andP;  Also included are aMIDI monitor, keyboard practice aids and auto-harmonization routines.andM;andgt;Digital Signal Processing (DSP) Objects.andP;  &quot;Virtual devices,&quot; such asfilters, delay lines and level meters, are included with MAX and can be usedwith Mac DSP cards from Digidesign Inc., Studer Editech and Reson8.andM;DSP Objects, developed at the Center for New Music and Audio Technology atthe University of California, Berkeley, can communicate with serial devices,such as laser disc players, and can also play snd resources through the Mac'son-board speaker system.andM;Opcode Systems Inc. is at 3641 Haven Drive, Suite A, Menlo Park, Calif.andO;94025-1010.andP;  Phone (415) 369-8131; fax (415) 369-1747.andO;</TEXT></DOC>